source_citation: Republican Party Platforms, Republican Party Platform of 1976 Online by Gerhard Peters and John T. Woolley, The American Presidency Project
title_or_description_from_source: Creating a "right to life" amendment for unborn children
text_of_amendment: We protest the Supreme Court's intrusion into the family structure through its denial of the parents' obligation and right to guide their minor children. The Republican Party favors a continuance of the public dialogue on abortion and supports the efforts of those who seek enactment of a constitutional amendment to restore protection of the right to life for unborn children.

source_citation: Republican Party Platforms, Republican Party Platform of 1980 Online by Gerhard Peters and John T. Woolley, The American Presidency Project
title_or_description_from_source: Creating a "right to life" amendment for unborn children
text_of_amendment: While we recognize differing views on this question among Americans in general—and in our own Party—we affirm our support of a constitutional amendment to restore protection of the right to life for unborn children.

source_citation: Republican Party Platforms, Republican Party Platform of 1984 Online by Gerhard Peters and John T. Woolley, The American Presidency Project
title_or_description_from_source: Creating a "right to life" amendment for unborn children
text_of_amendment: The unborn child has a fundamental individual right to life which cannot be infringed. We therefore reaffirm our support for a human life amendment to the Constitution, and we endorse legislation to make clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's protections apply to unborn children.

source_citation: Republican Party Platforms, Republican Party Platform of 1988 Online by Gerhard Peters and John T. Woolley, The American Presidency Project
title_or_description_from_source: Creating a "right to life" amendment for unborn children
text_of_amendment: We believe the unborn child has a fundamental individual right to life which cannot be infringed. We therefore reaffirm our support for a human life amendment to the Constitution, and we endorse legislation to make clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's protections apply to unborn children.
notes: Around this time, the abortion-related amendment proposals shift from being labelled as “Prohibit abortion; right to life” or just “prohibit abortion” to exclusively “right-to-life”

title_or_description_from_source: Creating a "right to life" amendment for unborn children
text_of_amendment: We support a human life amendment to the Constitution and legislation to make clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's protections apply to children before birth.

source_citation: NA
text_of_amendment: "The issue of abortion must be resolved by our democratic process. Once again I call on the Congress to make its voice heard against abortion on demand and to restore legal protections for the unborn whether by statute or constitutional amendment."
notes: This is not the first instance in which Reagan endorsed an amendment pertaining to the right to life, but it seems to be the most explicit and significant among those listed in the Presidential Papers. Prior to and after this statement, he spoke in favor of a similar amendment multiple times.

source_citation: York, Frank, "Public Opinion and Pro-Life Gains," Family Voice January/February 2000, 17.
notes: National Right to Life Committe. No date given, so went with first possible one based on it being a january/february issue

source_citation: Johnson, Donald Bruce, National Party Platforms of 1980. Urbana: University of Illinois Press, 1982, 14.
text_of_amendment: We support the efforts of those who seek enactment of the human life constitutional amendment, which will specifically mandate every branch of governmnet to protext this right for every human being at every stage of its development.

source_citation: Johnson, Donald Bruce, National Party Platforms of 1980. Urbana: University of Illinois Press, 1982, 99.
text_of_amendment: Protect all human life from the moment of conception until the time of natural death.
